                                    <p>Choose your type of accommodation. If it's not exactly one of these, select the closest.</p> 

                                    <h2>Whole house or bungalow</h2>
                                    <p>This is a property that hasn't been divided into separate flats or other units of accommodation.</p>

                                    <p>There are three types of whole house or bungalow:</p>
                                    
                                    <ul class="list">
                                    <li><strong>detatched:</strong> None of the living accommodation is attached to another property. It also includes houses or bungalows that are joined only by a garage.</li>
                                    <li><strong>semi-detatched:</strong> A house or bungalow that's joined to another house or bungalow on one side only.</li>
                                    <li><strong>terraced:</strong> A house in a row of at least three properties that share common walls. This includes end-of-terrace houses.</li>
                                    </ul>

                                    <h2>Flat, maisonette or apartment</h2>
                                    <p>There are three types of flat, maisonette or apartment:</p>                                    
                                    <ul class="list">
                                    <li><strong>in a purpose built block of flats or tenement:</strong> Your accommodation is part of a building that’s been designed for use as a block of flats. This includes buildings that were originally designed for another purpose, but have since been converted into flats or apartments, for example schools, churches or warehouses. It doesn’t include houses converted into flats</li>
                                    <li><strong>part of a converted or shared house (including bedsits):</strong> A house that’s been altered or divided to provide separate accommodation (such as flats or bedsits) for a number of households</li>
                                    <li><strong>in a commercial building (for example, in an office building, hotel or over a shop):</strong> The living accommodation is part of a building which isn’t only residential – it has another purpose</li>
